results.notes:
Solitary mushroom growing in boggy debris/tree litter, within a ‘lowland’ area in mixed woods; collected about 8 A.M., ~ 65 – 70 degrees or so:
Macro:
Pileus: about 2 to 2.25 cm broad, brown overall, lighter towards the margin, drying to a darker, more ‘greyish’-brown color, disc depressed-concave with rugose-venose-rivulose(ish) center, margin slightly sulcate and finely cracked/areolate showing white flesh underneath; Lamellae: ventricose, broad, free from stipe, light pinkish in color, edges concolorous; Stipe: even to slightly tapered towards base, dingy-pallid-white, appressed fibrillose with slight tomentose base, darkening slightly in handling; Odor/Taste: no noticeable smell and did not taste.

Micro:
Basidiospores: mostly subglobose to broadly ovoid/ellipsoid, infrequently nearly globose, hyaline to slightly yellowish in KOH, sometimes with thickened walls, ~ (5.1 – 5.3) 5.5 – 6.1 (6.2) x (4.3 – 4.6) 4.8 – 5.3 (5.5) μm; Q = 1.02 – 1.32; N = 25; (95% Conf: L x W = 5.6 – 5.9 × 4.9 – 5.2 μm; Q = 1.12 – 1.18); Basidia: generally 2 to 4-spored, generally clavate to clavate-fusiform, ~ 24 – 33 × 7 – 8 μm; Q = 3.0 – 4.1; Pleurocystidia: frequent, broadly clavate to broadly pyriform-ish to kind of sphaeropedunculate, typically with fairly long pedicel/tail, ~ 36 – 61 × 14 – 22 μm; Q = 2.5 – 3.1; (95% Conf: L x W = 43.9 – 53.3 × 15.9 – 19.0 μm; Q = 2.6 – 2.9); Cheilocystidia: abundant, mostly subutriform to fusiform-subclavate, ~ 35 – 45 × 9 – 14 μm; Q = 2.8 – 4.1; (95% Conf: L x W = 36.9 – 41.1 × 10.8 – 12.8 μm; Q = 3.1 – 3.6); Pileipellis: a hymeniderm consisting of predominantly brownish elements, mostly pyriform to obclavate, ~ 25 – 50 × 9 – 22 μm; Q = 1.6 – 3.6; (95% Conf: L x W = 35.3 – 39.6 × 13.8 16.4 μm; Q = 2.4 – 2.7); Caulocystidia: TBD; Clamp Connections: not observed in any hyphae/tissue.

results.notes:
Any Russula microscopists out there?
I could really use your opinion and help here.

How would you classify these pileocystidia?
Specifically in terms of:

1- Septa. I am definitely calling them septate, at least occasionally. What do you think? (update: few septa seems clear to everyone. Although there were some apparent aseptate pileicystidia, the most common number was maybe 2 septa, I’ve now observed up to 4-5 septa in one long cell)

2- Incrustations. I’m having doubts in calling this “incrustrated”. And if incrustrated, could one call them “pink”? (update: this is now the main question, “to incrustate or not to incrustate”, doesn’t seem so clear cut..)

Stained with:
- congo red
- sulphovanillin (saturated vanillin in ~33% H2SO4).
- Melzer (spores)
- acid fuchsine (0.4% fuchsine in 25% acetate) washed with 9.25%HCl

macro: broadleaves (Pistacia lentiscus, Viburnum tinus, Quercus faginea, Q. pseudococcifera), calcareous; peels to ~1/2; print ~IVb; no stipe context graying, context first sweet then very acrid; gills straight away very acrid; smell undetected; FeSO4 pinkish, guaiacol faint/negative, phenol slow from orange-pink to dark brown.

I’m leaning more towards subsect. Rubrinae (w/ incrustations), and a bit less to Urentes (no incrustations).

I’ve been using these papers as references:
- https://link.springer.com/…/p…/10.1007/s11557-017-1322-0.pdf
- https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00606-018-1506-3

results.notes:
Fruiting in grass beneath mature Douglas firs. Very fragile flesh(both cap and stems), taste-Mild, colors vinaceous when young, remaining vivacious at margins until near maturity with grayish nearly greenish yellow tones to cream at full cap expansion. Stems staining reddish yellow until fully dry. Spore print=creamy white. Dried multiple specimens for herbarium collection.
SPores= Elliptical to nearly round, warted.
Dried two caps on slides and obtained spore print/performed microscopy(multiple images included with this observation).

Description from SVIMS RUSSULA key-
“CAP 3-7 cm, pale or rosy vinaceous, grayish rose, or livid vinaceous to tan, or even yellowish green, center either paler or darker, very fragile, viscid drying pruinose or scurfy, 3/4 peeling, margin striate; flesh soft, very thin, white. TASTE mild. GILLS very pale cream, fairly distant, broad. STEM white, sometimes rose tinted, fragile. SPORE PRINT white to pale cream. HABITAT deciduous woods, especially beech. REMARKS Reported as rare by European authors. Grund found it common in conifer woods at low elevations around Puget Sound.”

Directly under Pinus pinaster next to Cistus salvifolius. Sandy soil, mostly acidic dominated by Pinus pinaster and Quercus suber. However with calcareous bedrock (very occasional Quercus faginea and Pinus pinea scatered).

- Very fragile fruitbodies.
- More slender than stocky, stipe/cap ratio close to 2 but not quite.
- Volva very fragile and easily fragmented, rather thin, attached in the lower part of stem, loose in the upper limit. Seems type IIa (?).
- Laminae slightly serrulate.

Micro still to be done in a few months.

Assuming this colletion is associated with the pines (and not the oaks or rockroses), I’m leaning more towards A. supravolvata, given the rather long and slender stem, plus the fragile volva of type II and adnate to the stipe. At least in comparison to A. mairei, apparently stockier with a thicker volva.

results.notes:
This lichen is above dry moss and stones with very weak fixation. Lower surface is whitish and has greenish and more rarely brownish tint. Rhizines are brown and short and their location is irregular. They are mainly at the end and in the centre of lobes, but not along very edge. They are hidden inside the convex lobes and there is some old moss with soil in bottom side of lobes. Apothecia are absent, but lots of picnidia. C test made greenish-yellow tint, but medulla is white. K test on very dry sample shows greenish-grey tint with red micro-cracks. K test of wet sample on crust and medulla shows orange-yellow then red up to dark blood-red and after drying reddish black.
Xanthoparmelia vagans according my guide books is similar to Xanthoparmelia wyomingica and they both have brown bottom surface. Observation 341532 is possible for both, but this one has whitish bottom side.
